  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Country Office 505233 HUB, NIAMEY, NIGER</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">The Islamist sect Boko Haram (BH) has been fighting a deadly insurgency in northern Nigeria for several years.The recent BH attacksagainst civil populations and Nigerian army led to the migration of people  towards Chad and Niger territory, mainly in the villages along the Komadougou River and Lake Chad Islands (Diffa region).The situation presented by the Niger government on December 16th, 2014 reported 96,019 refugees and returnees who arrived in Diffa region and are currently settled in 88 sites. However the situationis evolving with projection of 150,000 displaced when the census will be completed in the coming weeks or months and with more people fleeing unsafe zones in north-eastern Nigeria.
The security situation has deteriorated in recent months and BH still continues occupying some areas along the border between Diffa and Borno State.
There are also threats from BH to attack others localities in thecoming days and weeks.

The main site which received most returnees and refugees are Bosso with approximately 70,000, persons and Gagamari with approximately 15,000. The part of returnees (Niger citizens who used to live in Nigeria) is estimated 30%.
The main activities in Diffa region are livestock (more than 60%), agriculture and fishing.
The 2014 agro pastoral campaign resulted in a 53% ofdeficit of agricultural production making 156,480 vulnerable persons and the fodder deficit has been estimated at 1.8 million TMS  (corresponding to 62% of animals needs of the region). In addition the usual annual movement of about 28% of the herd observed from Niger to Nigeria (border transhumance) is being stopped while thousands of animals cross the border from Nigeria to Diffa Region because of the insecurity in northern Nigeria. In the other hand, animals that usually transit to Nigeria via Chad are obliged to crossDiffa and Zinder Regions before landing to Nigeria. These situations accentuate pressure on the already non sufficient pasture.

Sweet pepper farming and fishing that once were thriving are seriously undermined because of the lack of access to rivers in some areas and the limitation of commercial transactions.

Commercial activities between Diffa region and Nigeria are compromised because of insecurity, which significantly hinders the local economy heavily dependent on cross-border trade.

The lack of clean  water supply and sanitation, and the contaminated  Komadougou Yobe River has caused cholera outbreaks. The Ministry of Health reported a cholera outbreak in the Diffa region on December 13, 2014 and a total of 228 cases including 13 deaths were recorded on 22 December 2014.
The pressing needs of the displaced and host populations are reported in the next section</narrative>
  </description>
